<paragraph blockId="3.[136,1452,1606,2028]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,291,1606,1632]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Habitat:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Funez &amp; Hassemer" authorityYear="2021" box="[318,600,1606,1632]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humboldtiana">
<emphasis box="[318,600,1606,1632]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Persicaria humboldtiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
inhabits humid rocks along the riverbanks, at permanently humid spots due to constant splashing, and is susceptible (and seemingly resistant) to occasional flooding. The new species occurs in the same locality and environment as the narrowly endemics 
<taxonomicName authority="Hassemer" authorityName="Hassemer" authorityYear="2016" box="[879,1267,1678,1705]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Plantago" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humboldtiana">
<emphasis box="[879,1148,1678,1704]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Plantago humboldtiana</emphasis>
Hassemer
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis box="[1278,1300,1679,1704]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">in</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Hassemer, G. &amp; Ronsted, N. A. H." pageId="3" pageNumber="63" pagination="2050" refId="ref4782" refString="Hassemer, G. &amp; Ronsted, N. A. H. (2016) Yet another new species from one of the best-studied neotropical areas: Plantago humboldtiana (Plantaginaceae), an extremely narrow endemic new species from a waterfall in southern Brazil. PeerJ 4: e 2050. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.7717 / peerj. 2050" type="journal article" year="2016">Hassemer &amp; Rønsted (2016: 4–9)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Funez et al. (2020: 80 - 87)" authorityName="Funez" authorityPageNumber="80 - 87" authorityYear="2020" box="[422,999,1714,1741]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Onagraceae" genus="Ludwigia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humboldtiana">
<emphasis box="[422,691,1714,1740]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Ludwigia humboldtiana</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Funez, L. A. &amp; Farias, D. M. &amp; Hassemer, G. &amp; de Gasper, A. L." box="[697,999,1714,1741]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" pagination="77 - 89" refId="ref4521" refString="Funez, L. A., Farias, D. M., Hassemer, G. &amp; de Gasper, A. L. (2020) Ludwigia humboldtiana (Onagraceae), a narrowly endemic new species from the subtropical Atlantic Forest, southern Brazil. Phytotaxa 470: 77 - 89. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / phytotaxa. 470.1.3" type="journal article" year="2020">
Funez 
<emphasis box="[773,830,1714,1740]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">et al.</emphasis>
(2020: 80–87)
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, what demonstrates the high importance of this habitat for biodiversity conservation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[136,1452,1606,2028]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,437,1786,1812]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Conservation status:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Funez &amp; Hassemer" authorityYear="2021" box="[465,747,1786,1812]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humboldtiana">
<emphasis box="[465,747,1786,1812]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Persicaria humboldtiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is here assessed as Critically endangered CR according to the criterion B2a,b(iii) of IUCN (2019). The area of occupancy (AOO) of less than 
<quantity box="[1074,1137,1822,1851]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" unit="km" value="2.0">2 km</quantity>
², with only one population known. This population is located within an environmentally protected area (Emílio Fiorentino Battistella Natural Heritage Particular Reserve); nevertheless, the species unfortunately cannot be considered satisfactorily safe, because of the ongoing trend of reduction of environment protection areas in the region, due to the pressure caused by the agricultural advance in 
<collectingRegion box="[399,620,1966,1993]" country="Brazil" name="Santa Catarina" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Santa Catarina state</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hassemer, G. &amp; Ferreira, P. M. A. &amp; Trevisan, R." box="[635,874,1966,1993]" pageId="3" pageNumber="63" pagination="78 - 95" refId="ref4710" refString="Hassemer, G., Ferreira, P. M. A. &amp; Trevisan, R. (2015) A review of vascular plant endemisms in Santa Catarina, southern Brazil, highlights critical knowledge gaps and urgent need of conservation efforts. Journal of the Torrey Botanical Society 142: 78 - 95. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.3159 / torrey-d- 14 - 00033.1" type="journal article" year="2015">
Hassemer 
<emphasis box="[754,810,1966,1992]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
) and in 
<collectingCountry box="[964,1032,1966,1992]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="63">Brazil</collectingCountry>
as a whole, leading to the conversion of natural environments in agricultural and silvicutural lands.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[136,1452,158,545]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,265,158,184]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Notes:</emphasis>
—This species is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opiz, Seznam Rostlin Kveteny Ceske" authorityYear="1852" baseAuthorityName="Huds." box="[640,833,159,184]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="minor">
<emphasis box="[640,833,159,184]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Persicaria minor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a cosmopolitan species common in Eurasia and North America, with only one record in South America, in 
<taxonomicName authority="(Cialdella 1989)" baseAuthorityName="Cialdella" baseAuthorityYear="1989" box="[722,1026,194,220]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Fanerogamica" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="argentina">
Argentina (
<bibRefCitation author="Cialdella, A. M." box="[848,1018,194,220]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" pagination="179 - 246" refId="ref4071" refString="Cialdella, A. M. (1989) Revision de las especies argentinas de Polygonum s. l. (Polygonaceae). Darwiniana 29: 179 - 246." type="journal article" year="1989">Cialdella 1989</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Despite the similarities due the small size of the vegetative and reproductive characters of both species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Funez &amp; Hassemer" authorityYear="2021" box="[912,1099,230,256]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humboldtiana">
<emphasis box="[912,1099,230,256]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">P. humboldtiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is easily differentiated due its petiolate, broadly lanceolate leaves (
<emphasis box="[543,573,267,292]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">vs.</emphasis>
sessile, linear lanceolate leaves in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opiz, Seznam Rostlin Kveteny Ceske" authorityYear="1852" baseAuthorityName="Huds." box="[959,1053,267,292]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="minor">
<emphasis box="[959,1053,267,292]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">P. minor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Another very useful characteristic to distinguish these species is the size of the tepals, much smaller in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Funez &amp; Hassemer" authorityYear="2021" box="[885,1067,302,328]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humboldtiana">
<emphasis box="[885,1067,302,328]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">P. humboldtiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<quantity box="[1080,1213,302,329]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.5" metricValueMax="11.0" metricValueMin="8.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" unit="mm" value="0.95" valueMax="1.1" valueMin="0.8">0.8–1.1 mm</quantity>
long, with prominent veins (
<emphasis box="[211,242,339,364]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">vs.</emphasis>
2.5–3.0 mm long, with inconspicuous venation in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Opiz, Seznam Rostlin Kveteny Ceske" authorityYear="1852" baseAuthorityName="Huds." box="[810,905,339,364]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="minor">
<emphasis box="[810,905,339,364]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">P. minor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) (see 
<tableCitation box="[973,1054,338,364]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="4.[136,224,592,616]" captionText="TABLE 1. Morphological comparison between Persicaria humboldtiana and P. minor." pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Table 1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[136,1452,158,545]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">
Other species similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Funez &amp; Hassemer" authorityYear="2021" box="[474,759,374,400]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humboldtiana">
<emphasis box="[474,759,374,400]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">Persicaria humboldtiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are 
<taxonomicName authority="(Michaux 1803 a: 239) Small (1903: 378 - 379" authorityName="Small" authorityYear="1803" baseAuthorityName="Michaux" baseAuthorityPageNumber="239" baseAuthorityYear="1803" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hydropiperoides">
<emphasis box="[813,1025,374,400]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">P. hydropiperoides</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Michaux, A." box="[1043,1285,374,400]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" pagination="1 - 29" refId="ref5625" refString="Michaux, A. (1803 a) Flora Boreali-Americana, vol. 1. C. Crapelet, Paris and Strassburg, 330 pp., plates 1 - 29. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 330" type="book chapter" year="1803">Michaux 1803a: 239</bibRefCitation>
) 
<bibRefCitation author="Small, J. K." pageId="4" pageNumber="64" refId="ref6169" refString="Small, J. K. (1903) Flora of the Southeastern United States. Published by the author, New York, 1370 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 133" type="book" year="1903">Small (1903: 378–379</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 1330), 
<taxonomicName authority="Gray (1821: 269)" authorityName="Gray" authorityPageNumber="269" authorityYear="1821" box="[333,681,410,437]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="maculosa">
<emphasis box="[333,470,410,436]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">P. maculosa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Gray, S. F." box="[481,681,410,437]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" refId="ref4678" refString="Gray, S. F. (1821) A Natural Arrangement of British Plants, vol. 2. Baldwin, Gradock, and Joy, London, 757 pp." type="book" year="1821">Gray (1821: 269)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[741,855,411,436]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="setacea">
<emphasis box="[741,855,411,436]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">P. setacea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Baldwin 
<emphasis box="[979,1001,411,436]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">in</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Elliott, S." box="[1011,1226,410,437]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" refId="ref4326" refString="Elliott, S. (1817) Sketch of the Botany of South-Carolina and Georgia, part 1 (5). J. R. Schenck, Charleston, 606 pp., 6 plates. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 9508" type="book" year="1817">Elliott [1817: 455]</bibRefCitation>
) 
<bibRefCitation author="Small, J. K." box="[1244,1447,410,436]" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" refId="ref6169" refString="Small, J. K. (1903) Flora of the Southeastern United States. Published by the author, New York, 1370 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 133" type="book" year="1903">Small (1903: 379</bibRefCitation>
, 1330), but the size of the tepals are conspicuously bigger than in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Funez &amp; Hassemer" authorityYear="2021" box="[875,1059,446,472]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humboldtiana">
<emphasis box="[875,1059,446,472]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">P. humboldtiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; all these species has flowers with tepals longer than 
<quantity box="[342,427,482,509]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" unit="mm" value="2.5">2.5 mm</quantity>
long and sessile leaves, whereas 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Funez &amp; Hassemer" authorityYear="2021" box="[800,983,482,508]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Persicaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humboldtiana">
<emphasis box="[800,983,482,508]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="64">P. humboldtiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
tepals are 
<quantity box="[1103,1238,482,509]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.5" metricValueMax="11.0" metricValueMin="8.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="64" unit="mm" value="0.95" valueMax="1.1" valueMin="0.8">0.8–1.1 mm</quantity>
long and its leaves are petiolate.
</paragraph>
